one of two ways -\n\n1) Remix the project and build upon the existing example framework\n2) Backpack this MIDI sprite and add it to your own existing project\n\n====================================================================================================================================================\n\nQUICK OVERVIEW\n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nAdding music to your project -\n\n1) Convert the MIDI file to Hex or to Intel Hex 32 format using HxD (which is a free download)\n2) Use the MIDI: Menu broadcast to import songs into your project. Note that this can only be done from within the editor and you should save the project after adding songs\n\nPlaying music in your project -\n\n1) Select the song to play in the MIDI: Song variable (by either song number or name)\n2) Play the music by broadcasting MIDI: Play\n\n====================================================================================================================================================\n\nDETAILED INSTRUCTIONS\n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nThese are broadcasts that you can use:\n\nMIDI: Menu - this brings up the toolkit menu so that songs can be added or removed from your project. This should be called using a broadcast and wait\nMIDI: Play - this will play the song indexed by the MIDI: Song variable. Normally this would be used with a broadcast (without wait) so that your game will continue running with the music playing\nMIDI: Stop - this stops the current music\nMIDI: Toggle pause - this will pause or unpause the current music\n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nThese are broadcasts made from the MIDI toolkit:\n\nMIDI: Song completed callback - add a receiver for this broadcast if you want to perform an action when a song has completed. In this example we start playing the next song in the list\nMIDI: Reset visualisation - add a receiver for this broadcast if you need to initialise any visualisations when a new song is played\nMIDI: Update visualisation - add a receiver for this broadcast if you want to read information about the notes being played each frame (usually for visualisations)\n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nThese are global variables used with the MIDI toolkit:\n\nMIDI: Song - Which song to play when you broadcast MIDI: Play. You can set MIDI: Song to either the number or the name of the song\nMIDI: Song count - This tells you how many songs have been imported into the project. Note that you shouldn't change the value of this variable\n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nThese are the global data lists used with the MIDI toolkit:\n\nMIDI: Midi songs: This contains the list of song names for all MIDI songs imported into the project. You can use this with MIDI: Song to get the song name of the currently playing music\nMIDI: Visualisation data: This contains information about all notes being played on the current frame (and is used from the MIDIL Update visualisation callback broadcast)\n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nAny variable, list or broadcast that begins with z_MIDI: is for internal use by the MIDI Toolkit and should not be used in your own projects.\n\n====================================================================================================================================================\n\nVISUALISATIONS\n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nIf you want to implement your own visualisation data then you should make use of the MIDI: Reset visualisation and MIDI: Reset visualisation broadcast callbacks (as described above). The MIDI: Visualisation update callback can make use of data in the MIDI: Visualisation data list. Each frame that list contains details about all of the notes being played on that frame. For each note being played there are four pieces of information in that data. These are -\n\npitch: a number between 0 and 127 which represents the note being played\nduration: the length that the note will be played in seconds\ninstrument: the instrument being used. Instruments 0 to 127 are musical instruments. Anything above that are percussion instruments\nvolume: how loud the note is being played (from 0 to 127)\n\nHave a look at the \"Get visualisation data\" helper function in the Visualisation sprite for a good method of accessing this data. What that function does is to pull the first four items from the list and to put them into variables called pitch, duration, instrument and volume. It then removes those items from the list. By repeatedly calling that function until the list is empty, you are able to access and use whatever data you wish about all the notes being played on that frame."}},"currentCostume":1,"costumes":[{"assetId":"8703937236f828f89eae5c115251d6a3","name":"Sprite
